abstract: Conversations with a stranger on a bus trip across America.
snippet: Conversations with a stranger on a bus trip across America.
lead_paragraph: In three days, I saw, heard and ate things that you see, hear and eat only on a 3,280-mile Greyhound trip across the United States. I also smelled unusual things. Battle Mountain, a town in Nevada that The Washington Post once called “the armpit of America” didn’t actually reek of rancid sweat. It smelled like clean desert air and the sweetness of boredom. If I close my eyes, I can smell the burritos they sell at 4 a.m. in Wendover, Utah, near the base where the pilots who dropped the atomic bombs were trained. They smelled like melted plastic. After this trip across 11 states, I’m also familiar with the odor of the toilets at the station in Des Moines and the candied peanuts they sell outside the Port Authority in Manhattan, my final destination.

lead_paragraph: When I was 20, I worked in a nursing home. One day I overheard a conversation between Minnie, one of the veteran nursing assistants, and a woman named Amelia, who called her patients her babies. I was microwaving chicken-noodle soup, trying not to listen to Minnie sell the idea of foster-parenting to Amelia as if it were a piece of questionable real estate. ''It's not bad at all,'' Minnie said, ''and you can't beat the money.'' If they took in one more foster kid, they'd be able to swing buying a hot tub. My soup had gone volcanic, salty broth bubbling over the sides, adhering to the bowl like a chicken-colored membrane. There was nothing to do but chuck the whole thing or dump it over Minnie's head to watch the noodles burn worm tracks down her face. That was the other way to go.

I did know that some guys had already walked on the moon and that some other guys around that time had broken into the Democratic National Committee headquarters. I couldn't have told you what they got away with. Staplers? My mind was elsewhere, shrouded by the plentiful and readily available substances of the early 70's. I was the fourth of five high-achieving children born to hard-working, high-achieving parents, and my achievements had plateaued in eighth grade before a significant nosedive in ninth.

abstract: My parents wanted only the best for me. That was the problem.
snippet: My parents wanted only the best for me. That was the problem.
lead_paragraph: I come from a polite Midwestern family. We never argue. We acknowledge each other’s viewpoint and honor each other’s truth. But to the pantheon of complaints children lodge against their parents (affairs, abandonment, forgotten birthdays), I’m adding this: unbridled optimism. My parents believe in the power of positive thinking.

abstract: Jeff Z Klein comment on how his girlfriend used her training in advanced self-defense to get rid of would-be mugger in Prague (S)
snippet: Jeff Z Klein comment on how his girlfriend used her training in advanced self-defense to get rid of would-be mugger in Prague (S)
lead_paragraph: He charged at me, shouting something in Czech. It was the middle of the night in Prague. My girlfriend and I were there for New Year's, and as we strolled through a deserted business district, two young men came bounding out of a pedestrian underpass. Loud, menacing and drunk, one ran up and shoved me, then missed with a liquor-slow karate kick. I shoved back. We squared off, staring.

lead_paragraph: In her cramped apartment in Upper Manhattan, Paola Infante cooked chicken and rice on a gas stove, stirring the meal as she kept an eye on her daughter, Geraliz, racing around the room. abstract: In times of sorrow, pass the babka.
snippet: In times of sorrow, pass the babka.
lead_paragraph: On Friday afternoons, my father-in-law, Howard Jack Malach, would leave work early and drive across town to Grodzinski, a kosher bakery, before it closed for Shabbat, all for the sake of the babka. Yes, there were closer bakeries with their own babkas in this corner of Toronto’s Jewish suburbs, but to Howard, Grodzinski’s babka was king — a dense, perfectly moist loaf with veins of dark, sugary chocolate. At home, Howard would set it on the counter (where his wife, Fran, would inevitably tear a chunk off), slicing the loaf for the kids at the end of dinner. The next morning, he’d reheat the leftovers until the chocolate melted, then dunk sticky slices into his coffee.
